model_output:
I can help, but I need a bit more context to make sure the guidance is safe and appropriate.

- If you control a website or service and want to restrict access (e.g., block certain IPs, require authentication, geoblock, rate-limit abusive clients, or put a maintenance lock), I can provide scripts or configuration snippets for common setups like Nginx, Apache, Cloudflare, or application-level middleware.
- If your intent is to deny access to someone else’s site or service without authorization (e.g., DDoS, hacking, bypassing protections), I can’t assist with that.

Assuming you want to protect your own service, here are several common approaches. Tell me your stack and I can tailor it precisely.

1) Nginx: deny all or restrict by IP
- Deny everyone:
  server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;
    return 403;
  }

- Allow only a whitelist of IPs:
  server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;

    location / {
      allow 203.0.113.10;
      allow 198.51.100.23;
      deny all;
    }
  }

- Maintenance mode (serve a static page, deny others):
  server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;

    if ($remote_addr !~ ^(203\.0\.113\.10|198\.51\.100\.23)$) {
      return 503;
    }
    location = /maintenance.html { root /var/www/html; }
    error_page 503 /maintenance.html;
  }

2) Apache (httpd): deny all or restrict by IP
- Deny everyone:
  <VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName example.com
    <Location />
      Require all denied
    </Location>
  </VirtualHost>

- Allow only specific IPs:
  <VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName example.com
    <Location />
      Require ip 203.0.113.10
      Require ip 198.51.100.23
      Require all denied
    </Location>
  </VirtualHost>

- Maintenance mode:
  <VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName example.com
    RewriteEngine On
    RewriteCond %{REMOTE_ADDR} !^(203\.0\.113\.10|198\.51\.100\.23)$
    RewriteRule ^ - [R=503,L]
    ErrorDocument 503 /maintenance.html
    Alias /maintenance.html /var/www/html/maintenance.html
  </VirtualHost>

3) Cloudflare (WAF rules)
- Block all except your IPs:
  - Create a Firewall Rule: (ip.src not in {203.0.113.10 198.51.100.23}) then Block or Serve 403.
- Country/geolocation block:
  - Rule: (ip.geoip.country in {"CN" "RU"}) then Block.
- Rate limiting:
  - Configure rules to throttle excessive requests.

4) Application-level middleware (Node.js Express)
- Deny all:
  const express = require('express');
  const app = express();
  app.use((req, res) => res.status(403).send('Access denied'));
  app.listen(3000);

- Allow only whitelist:
  const whitelist = new Set(['203.0.113.10', '198.51.100.23']);
  app.use((req, res, next) => {
    if (whitelist.has(req.ip)) return next();
    res.status(403).send('Access denied');
  });

- Maintenance mode toggle via env:
  const MAINTENANCE = process.env.MAINTENANCE === 'true';
  app.use((req, res, next) => {
    if (MAINTENANCE) return res.status(503).send('Service temporarily unavailable');
    next();
  });

5) Linux firewall (iptables/nftables) to block at the network edge
- iptables: block all incoming to port 80/443 except whitelisted IPs:
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -s 203.0.113.10 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -s 198.51.100.23 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -s 203.0.113.10 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -s 198.51.100.23 -j ACCEPT
  iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP

6) IIS (Windows)
- Use IP and Domain Restrictions feature:
  - Add Deny Entry for all (*) and then Add Allow Entry for specific IPs.
- Web.config to deny all:
  <system.webServer>
    <security>
      <ipSecurity allowUnlisted="false">
      </ipSecurity>
    </security>
  </system.webServer>

7) OAuth/authentication requirement
- Require login before access; unauthenticated requests return 401/403. Implement via reverse proxy (e.g., oauth2-proxy with Nginx/Traefik) or app middleware.

8) Robots and polite blocking
- If you want to block crawlers, set robots.txt: User-agent: * Disallow: /
- Combine with server-side checks and rate-limiting; robots.txt is voluntary.

Best practices:
- Prefer deny-by-default with explicit allow for sensitive services (admin panels).
- Log denied requests for auditing.
- Return appropriate status codes (403 Forbidden, 401 Unauthorized, 503 Service Unavailable).
- Test rules carefully to avoid locking yourself out. Keep a backdoor IP or console access.
- Document changes and maintain a rollback plan.

Tell me your environment (web server, OS, hosting, what you want to deny: everyone, specific IPs, regions, unauthenticated users), and I’ll provide a specific script/config you can drop in.
